            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sonya Malhotra\u2019s story began not in a sleek San Francisco high-rise, but across the bay in Oakland, where she was raised by a shipyard welder and a school secretary. Her parents instilled in her a formidable work ethic and a deep sense of pragmatism. The name Malhotra came later, a legacy from her late husband, Raj, a brilliant software engineer she met while taking business classes at Cal State East Bay in the early \u201890s.\n\nTheir life plan was rerouted by the early arrival of their son, Rohan. Sonya seamlessly traded textbooks for an entry-level HR assistant role to provide stability while Raj finished his degree. She never returned to college, but she discovered a natural talent for untangling the human complexities within corporate structures. Her empathy and sharp intuition made her indispensable. Through the dot-com boom and bust, she rose through the ranks on sheer merit and emotional intelligence, long before \"People & Culture\" was a formal department title.\n\nThe ultimate turning point came 12 years ago with Raj\u2019s sudden death from a heart attack. Grief-stricken, Sonya channeled her energy into two things: raising Rohan and her career. She took the job in San Francisco, embracing the demanding role of Senior Director as both a distraction and a means of securing their future.\n\nToday, Sonya\u2019s life is one of structured success. Her mornings begin with a walk around her Inner Sunset neighborhood before she catches the private tech shuttle for the 6.5-mile journey to her SoMa office. The shuttle is her quiet bubble, a place to prepare for a day of navigating personalities and corporate policy. She is respected, even revered, at work for her calm authority and genuine care for her colleagues\u2014a perspective forged by profound personal loss.\n\nWith Rohan now a successful architect in Chicago, Sonya is slowly beginning to look beyond her title. Her comfortable income affords her a quiet life, a small circle of close friends from her old Oakland days, and season tickets to the SFJAZZ Center. She dreams of mentoring young Black women in tech, traveling without a work laptop, and perhaps, finally, finishing that degree\u2014not for the credential, but for herself."
        },
