            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe still remembers the cheap whiteboard propped against the wall of their first Oakland apartment. Raj, his eyes on fire with ideas, was mapping out the architecture for a future software company while she sketched a corresponding business plan. Rohan wasn't even a thought yet. In that moment, surrounded by takeout containers and limitless hope, she felt the sheer, thrilling power of their combined ambition. That memory became her anchor, the pure blueprint of the life they were supposed to build together, long before it all changed.\n\n2.\nThe landline rang while she was rocking a fussy, teething Rohan. It was the job offer\u2014the HR assistant role with steady pay and benefits. Looking from the phone to her son's sleeping face, she felt the weight of his future settle on her. In that instant, she chose stability over her own diploma without a second thought. It wasn\u2019t a painful sacrifice, but a transfer of ambition. It cemented a pragmatism in her that would define her entire career: always put the needs of your people first.\n\n3.\nShe walked into their quiet house after leaving the hospital, the silence deafening. Raj\u2019s running shoes were still by the front door, caked with a bit of mud from the morning jog he never finished. The sight of them\u2014so ordinary and permanent\u2014shattered her. That single, mundane detail marked the precise moment her life broke in two. Grief wasn't a dramatic wave; it was the sudden, quiet, irrefutable absence of everything. It forged an unbreakable resolve in her to simply keep going for Rohan.\n\n4.\nHer first morning on the tech shuttle felt like a journey to a foreign country. As the bus crossed the Bay Bridge, leaving her Oakland life in the rearview, a cold dread mixed with her resolve. She was no longer part of a \u2018we\u2019; she was just Sonya, a widowed mother entering a world of brilliant young minds she was now responsible for. That ride wasn\u2019t about convenience; it was a conscious, terrifying step into the new, lonely life she had to build. It was the day she started building her armor.\n\n5.\nLast winter at the SFJAZZ Center, she found herself completely lost in a saxophone solo\u2014a sound so full of sorrow and hope it vibrated in her bones. For the first time in years, she wasn't thinking about quarterly reports or even about Rohan. She was just a woman, alone in a crowd, moved by music. In that moment of pure, selfish feeling, she recognized a flicker of the person she was before the grief and the title. It was a quiet permission slip to finally start living for herself again."
